{{!
This route will respond with a valid HTML document with the results returned from the API. The title of the document
should be "Meals Found". You should have the title set as the <title> element of the HTML document and as an h1 in your
    document. In an h2 element, you will print the supplied keyword.

    Your page should reference a CSS file, /public/css/styles.css; this file should have at least 10 rulesets you must
    use at least 5 of them on this page.

    You should have a main element, and inside of the main element have a ol tag that has a list of all meals
    matching the keyword found in the request body in the following format (after searching chicken). Each list item
    will show the image of the meal, and the meal title, it should link to your /meal/:id route. One of your CSS rules,
    should scale the image from the data so it is just a thumbnail. Otherwise, the image will be huge! You will lose
    points if you make it that huge. A good width is 100px and a good height is 100px. DO NOT FORGET TO ADD THE ALT
    ATTRIBUTE TO the Image. Set it to be "[meal name] Image" as shown below.

    <ol>
        <li>
            <a href="/meal/52795">Chicken Handi <br> <img class="searchResultImage" alt="Chicken Handi Image"
                    src="https://www.themealdb.com/images/media/meals/wyxwsp1486979827.jpg"></a>
        </li>
        <li>
            <a href="/meal/52846">Chicken & mushroom Hotpot <br> <img class="searchResultImage"
                    alt="Chicken & mushroom Hotpot Image"
                    src="https://www.themealdb.com/images/media/meals/uuuspp1511297945.jpg"></a>
        </li>
        <li>
            <a href="/meal/52818">Chicken Fajita Mac and Cheese <br> <img class="searchResultImage"
                    alt="Chicken Fajita Mac and Cheese Image"
                    src="https://www.themealdb.com/images/media/meals/qrqywr1503066605.jpg"></a>
        </li>
    </ol>

}}
